Scope Conditions


At one level, contact and conflict theories seem to make opposing predictions about the relationship between out-group size and prejudice.

However, in the social sciences, theoretical predictions rarely hold all of the time.

For instance, Laurence argues contact theory is more appropriate when segregation is low, and constrict theory is more approproriate when segregation is high.

The concept of segregation constitutes a scope condition that is, it delimits the circumstances or the types of cases where a theory is supposed to apply.

While scope conditions may not be explicitly spelled out, they are (almost) alwas there, and we should be careful about extrapolating a theory beyond its scope conditions. By the same token, simply because a theory does not apply in all circumstances does not mean that the theory is wrong.

Take the following theoretical propositions and see if you can come up with some scope conditions:

  • If you make something cheaper, more people will buy it.
  • Politicians will adjust their positions towards the median voter.
  • Pure liquid H20 will turn to ice at 0 degrees celcius.

Measuring Diversity

Many researchers use an index of Ethnolinguistic Fractionalization (ELF) to measure diversity.

Imagine we had groups g1 , g2 , g3 , gn, where gn represents the percentage of individuals from group n in the population.

ELF = 1 - ( g12 + g22 + g32 + gn2 )

Note that ( g12 + g22 + g32 + gn2 ) = probability that two individuals will belong to the same group.

Thus, the ELF measures the probability that two randomly-selected will belong to different groups.

ELF ranges from 0 (completely homogenous) to 1 (every individual belongs to a unique group).

Measurement Problem: Color-Blindness

Note that ELF treats all groups in a color-blind way. In other words, the following two neighborhoods are scored as equivalently diverse:

  • A: 70% white, 30% black
  • B: 30% white, 70% black

Discussion: do you think social relations would be similiar in these two areas? Whats missing from the color-blind view of groups?

Measuring Segregation: The Index of Dissimilarity (D)

D is one of the most commonly used measure of segregation between 2 groups. It compares their relative distribution across neighborhoods within the larger city.

Formula


\(D = \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n} |\frac{a_{i}}{A} - \frac{b_{i}}{B}|\)

  • A = Total City Population of A
  • B = Total City Population of B
  • \(a_{i}\) = Population of a in neighborhod i
  • \(b_{i}\) = Population of b in neighborhod i

D ranges from 0 to 100.

0 indicates conditions of total integration under which both groups are distributed in the same proportions across all neighborhoods.

100 indicates conditions of total segregation such that the members of one group are located in completely different neighborhoods than the second group.


Intuitively, D measures the percentage of one group that would have to move across neighborhoods to be distributed the same way as the second group.

MAUP 3: The Problem of Boundaries

Conceptually, segregation is about how groups are arranged in space.

However, D calculates segregation based on how groups are distributed across (arbitrarily drawn) administrative units.

Final food for thought:

Note that in Enos study, the treatment was the presence / absence of a population that was both poor and black. In fact, many segregated communities are both racially and economically marginalized. What does this suggest to you about the drivers of intergroup conflict?

More broadly, the readings for this week show that the presence of a segregated, poor, marginalized minority group tends to elicit group conflict. Thats not exactly surprising! But its a big step to go from that evidence to an argument about the general effects of diversity or segregation.

Heres a couple of thought experiments:

  1. How would whites prejudice change if their poor, black neighbors on the other side of the tracks were all of a sudden dispersed into white neighborhoods (i.e.segregation decreases, but diversity and the racial socioeconomic gap remains the same)?
  2. How would whites prejudice change if instead of living near a poor, black enclave they found themselves living next to an enclave full of rich sheiks from Saudi Arabia?
